The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, March 25, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, March 24: Petrol and diesel prices are likely to go up by at least Rs 2 per litre after the Lok Sabha polls, once the current freeze on revising prices in step with the cost of the raw material, crude oil, is lifted. The public sector oil companies, Indian Oil, Hindustan Petroleum, Bharat Petroleum and IBP, are estimated to have taken a hit of around Rs 3,600 crore during January-March 2004 so as not to hurt the governments India Shining image during the polls, industry sources said.																								 Washington, March 24: General Motors Corp is planning to shift white collar jobs to other countries, including India. The move is part of a cost-cutting programme which aims to slash GMs manufacturing costs by 25 per cent by the end of 2005, an internal report of the company said.																								 New Delhi, March 24: IFCIs employees union today proposed a mega merger of four development financial institutions, IFCI, IDBI, IIBI and IDFC, to create a stronger and diversified institution. 																								 London, March 24: International rating agency Moodys today retained the BA2 rating on Tata Motors Ltds debt paper but changed its outlook to positive from negative.																								 Calcutta, March 24: Uco Bank has raised Rs 300 crore from the capital market via private placement of unsecured redeemable non-convertible subordinated bonds.
